frameDefinitions: A Submittor gives Documents to an Authority so that they can be processed as part of an application, evaluation or other official or bureaucratic process.

The answer to one open question, the Outcome, is dictated (partially or completely) by the answer to another open question, the Determinant, i.e. if the answer to the Determinant is known, the answer to the Outcome can be predicted.
This frame contains items which, when manipulated, alter the function of some device, internal or external.
A Controlling_entity, Controlling_situation, or Controlling_variable control a Dependent_entity, Dependent_situation, or Dependent_variable.
This Frame is concerned with evaluating an Evaluee as being suitable for a Purpose or a User, presupposing some choice that is being made about which Evaluee to use for the Purpose or User.
An Agent changes a Part of a complex entity with regard to some Feature in order to achieve some Imposed_purpose affected by the Feature.
frameExamples: I  was sure I had passed as soon as I <t>handed</t> <t>in</t> the test. DNI
Economic policy is partially a <t>function</t> of cultural values.
This <t>button</t> makes the radio turn on.
(1) We need to build more houses <t>suitable</t> for local residents.
I need to <t>adjust</t> the thermostat to around 80 degrees when she visits.
listRoleDefinitions: The person that begins in possession of the <fen>Documents</fen> and gives them over into the possession of the <fen>Authority</fen> for processing.
The individual or organization that ends up in possession of the <fen>Documents</fen> and processes them.
The artifacts containing content, typically in the form of text and images, that the Submittor gives to the <fen>Authority</fen>.
The time period during which the <fen>Submittor</fen> gives the <fen>Documents</fen> to the <fen>Authority</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Submittor</fen> gives the <fen>Documents</fen> to the <fen>Authority</fen>.
An open question that is (to some degree) predictable from the Determinant.
An open question that determines the <fen>Outcome</fen>.
This role identifies the entity or substance that is designed to have a particular <fen>Use</fen>. This is often an incorporated FE.
A thing or person whose behavior controls a <fen>Dependent_entity</fen>, <fen>Dependent_situation</fen>, or <fen>Dependent_variable</fen>.
An entity, usually a thing, that is influenced in its behavior by a <fen>Controlling_entity</fen> or an <fen>Controlling_situation</fen>.
The <fex name='tim'>Time</fex> at which the controlling occurs.
The location at which the controlling occurs.
This Frame Element marks constituents expressing the entity that is judged to be more or less suitable for some <fen>Purpose</fen> or <fen>User</fen>.
This Frame Element marks constituents that express the <fen>Purpose</fen> for which the <fen>Evaluee</fen> is judged to be suitable or unsuitable.
This role marks expressions that indicate a <fen>User</fen> to whom
The individual that controls the value of a <fen>Feature</fen>.
The part of the complex entity which is changed in the process of adjusting.
The <fen>Feature</fen> with respect to which the <fen>Part</fen> is adjusted.
The time at which the adjusting occurs.
The location where the adjusting takes place.
listRoleExamples: The Human Services financial worker cannot decide if you will get food support benefits until <fex>you</fex> turn in the form and needed verifications.
If an application is late, whether you submitted it late <fex>to us</fex> or it was held up at your Command, NMETC will not be able to fund registration fees.

Once you have submitted <fex>the form</fex>, a request to make an oral statement will be
generated based on the information you supplied.
Price, in such a case, depends <fex>only on the whim of the supplier</fex>.
Being a project leader is not a job for which <fex>everybody</fex> is suited.
We need to plan more buildings suitable <fex>for disabled people</fex>.
She adjusted <fex>the injectors</fex> to make the mixture leaner.
She adjusted <fex>the temperature of the oven</fex> so that the pie crust would brown a little.
